    "abstractNote": "Rest is an important soteriological and christological concept in the third century apocryphal <i>Acts of Thomas</i>. The forty-five references to rest (\u1f00\u03bd\u03ac\u03c0\u03b1\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 and its cognates) mark rest as a significant theme of the work. This article provides an analysis of the use of \u1f00\u03bd\u03ac\u03c0\u03b1\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 in the Greek <i>Acts of Thomas</i>. Rest is a rich and multifaceted motif that expresses both present experience and future hope. It is an attribute of Christ but also a benefit of being in union with Christ. Rest, achieved through rigorous \u201choliness\u201d (abstinence, especially from sex), is synonymous with salvation. The <i>Acts of Thomas</i>\u2019 understanding of rest is rooted in Jewish rest tradition, which the author/compiler has christianized and enriched with an ascetical emphasis that is characteristic of Syriac spirituality.",
